entry.title: Include AllocationStackTraceRecorder into Crashpad report - 3/N
entry.content:
With Arm's Memory Tagging Extension enabled, a process shall receive a

SIGSEGV if it encounters a mismatch in memory tags. To help developers

analyse problems like this, we want to include a history of the most

recent allocations and frees in the crashpad report.



This CL extends the allocation_recorder component. It now locates the

AllocationTraceRecorder from the terminating process and copies it into

the crash handler. The crashpad report still only contains simple

messages.

entry.title: Don't use getifaddrs() in the network service
entry.content:
HaveOnlyLoopbackAddressesSlow() uses getifaddrs() on all Posix platforms

to check if the machine only has loopback interfaces. getifaddrs() uses

netlink and so it isn't compatible with the Linux network sandbox.



This CL adds HaveOnlyLoopbackAddressesFast() which uses cached

information to compute the same result, and it should be faster and

should run on the main thread with no task posting. This requires no

system calls or interaction with the system, so it runs easily in the

sandbox.

entry.title: [TTFRefactor] Move ShowTouchToFill call into ShowPasswordSuggestions
entry.content:
ShowKeyboardReplacingSurface will be removed from mojom interface as

it's exessive. Instead, ShowKeyboardReplacingSurface will be called from

ContentPasswordManagerDriver::ShowPasswordSuggestions and so the logic

which handles the keyboard replacing surfaces will be entirely on the

browser side.



This CL:

- Introduces the PasswordSuggestionBottomSheetV2 feature flag.

- With the feature flag on, it doesn't call

`TryToShowKeyboardReplacingSurface` in the `AutofillAgent`. Instead, it

calls `ShowTouchToFill` from `ShowPasswordSuggestions` in the driver.

- Introduces the state into the `TouchToFillController`, which reflects

whether the TTF is being displayed.



P. S. With the PasswordSuggestionBottomSheetV2 flag on, the

auto-submission and the keyboard suppression doesn't work in the current

implementation. This is going to be fixed in the following CLs.

entry.title: Revert "[mojo] Fix multi-broker networks on Windows"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 458f376a8c94c6113a2c77f8d050c7338583d370.



Reason for revert: InvitationTest.NonBrokerToNonBroker failing on Linux Chromium OS ASan LSan Tests (1)

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Chromium%20OS%20ASan%20LSan%20Tests%20%281%29/51494/overview



Original change's description:

> [mojo] Fix multi-broker networks on Windows

>

> Handle passing between a non-broker and a secondary broker in

> multi-broker networks was broken on Windows. This change fixes it.

>

> The fix is specifically for this scenario:

>

> - a broker X is connected to another broker Y

> - X has a handle to Y's process; but Y has no handle to X's

> - X is the broker for (+ has a process handle for) non-broker Z

> - Y and Z require an introduction

> - X gives Y a transport for Z, including Z's process handle

>

> The bug is that because Y doesn't have a process handle for X,

> it will ignore *all* process handles sent by X, including the

> process handle for Z. As a result neither Y nor Z will have

> the other's process handle, and at least one must have the

> other's process handle in order for other handles to be

> transmissible between them.

>

> The fix is simply to remove the unnecessary constraint, as it

> appears to provide no security value: it doesn't matter if Y

> has no process handle for X. It can still accept handles to

> other processes from X.

>

> Fixed: 1432382

entry.title: [media] Create VideoToolboxVideoDecoder
entry.content:
VideoToolboxVideoDecoder is a VideoDecoder implemented using

VideoToolbox platform decoding. It is intended to replace

VTVideoDecodeAccelerator which was written using VDA interfaces.



VideoToolboxVideoDecoder is composed of five major pieces:

- VideoToolboxVideoDecoder implements the VideoDecoder interface and

handles frame ordering.

- H264Decoder parses bitstreams.

- VideoToolboxH264Accelerator packages bitstreams for VideoToolbox.

- VideoToolboxDecompressionInterface configures and operates the

VideoToolbox platform APIs.

- VideoToolboxFrameConverter produces VideoFrame objects backed by

VideoToolbox IOSurfaces.



Enable with --enable-features=VideoToolboxVideoDecoder,UseMultiPlaneFormatForHardwareVideo,PassthroughYuvRgbConversion

entry.title: CacheEviction and ExpiredEntryDeletion task for Shared Dictionary
entry.content:
This CL itoroduces CacheEvictionTask and ExpiredDictionaryDeletionTask

in SharedDictionaryManagerOnDisk.



These tasks are triggered when:

- SharedDictionaryManagerOnDisk is created.

- SetCacheMaxSize is called.

- A new dictionary is added. (CacheEvictionTask is triggered only if

the total dictionary size exceeds `cache_max_size_`.)

- ClearData is called.



Also this CL introduces Net.SharedDictionaryManagerOnDisk.

TotalDictionarySizeWhenAdded UMA which is the total size of shared

dictionaries on disk, recorded when SharedDictionaryManagerOnDisk

succeeded to store a dictionary in disk cache and database.

entry.title: Stop network service from caching requests via DriveHttpClient
entry.content:
When DriveFS attempts to make a request via the Chrome network service

it appears like there's an intermediate injection of the If-None-Match

HTTP header to try to leverage the e-tag header. Unfortunately this

currently causes the Files.get API to fail. To temporarily get around

this, pass the `Cache-Control` header to avoid any of the caching

instrumentation from adding headers.



This should be fine to do as the DriveFS layer should perform it's own

caching and use changes to request from the server. This does, however,

have the temporary side effect of any other requests (e.g.

drive.google.com) not being retrieved from cached in the event the same

item is retrieved from 2 separate calls.



Bug: b:284789869

entry.title: [iOS] Remove duplicate code path for reordering overflow menu
entry.content:
This CL removes the duplicate code path for reordering badged overflow

menu items (one for with smart sorting, one for without). It uses the

following principles:



- NSArray is solely used to communicate above

this class. Within this class and below this class, it uses

DestinationRanking (= std::vector) to hold

destination orderings.

- The _ranking instance variable is modified instead of passing around

vectors



Now, the behavior is as follows:

1. Use provided default ranking as a default if there is no ranking

currently (either because this is the first use of the menu or user

never used smart sorting in the past).

2. Ask Smart Sorting to sort, if available.

3. Reorder the menu due to badging, if necessary (in the future, this

could be refactored into a separate module, like Smart Sorting).
